  <reasoning-chapter-placement>
    Final Act 2 chapter and critical turning point. Elder Heartwood's response arrives after weeks of waiting—the answer they pinned all their hopes on. But it's completely inadequate, revealing a fundamental category error. Elder Heartwood is so ancient, so removed, operating on such different timescales that the response is irrelevant to Kira's actual survival needs. Maybe talks about seasonal cycles when asked about human nutrition, or discusses pre-visitor ecosystems when asked about current crisis, or fundamentally misunderstands what "human" means.

    This is the "Wizard of Oz" moment—the ultimate authority they journeyed to consult has no real answers. The plants are crushed; they were SO confident Elder Heartwood would solve everything. But the realization becomes liberating rather than devastating: everything they accomplished during the journey and waiting period was REAL learning. The plants working with Kira have already learned more practical wisdom about cross-framework care than Elder Heartwood knows.

    Sets up Act 3's authority vacuum: no procedures work, no elders have answers. They must rely on themselves and each other. This failure is necessary for both Kira (stops deferring to external authority) and plants (find authentic voices instead of waiting for wisdom from above).
  </reasoning-chapter-placement>
  <chapter-objective>
