  <character-development>
    Kira: Experiences the disappointment but recovers faster than the plants—she's been learning not to defer to authority. Helps plants see that their own learning is valid. Steps into a leadership role not by asserting dominance but by naming what they've already accomplished. Growing confidence in her own judgment.

    Holloway: Most shaken by Elder Heartwood's failure—has been clinging to the idea that proper authority will provide the framework they need. Must confront that procedures and authorities aren't sufficient. Beginning to trust the messy, improvised learning they've been doing.

    Scout: Has been communicating non-verbally all along, never waited for Elder Heartwood to validate that approach. The failure doesn't devastate Scout the same way—Scout already trusted their own methods.

    Plants collectively: Shaken faith in external wisdom. Must confront that they've been learning genuine care through trial and error, relationship-building, paying attention to Kira specifically. Their own experience is valid knowledge, not just "waiting for the real answer."

    Buddy: Learning alongside everyone that teaching moments and official protocols aren't always the answer. Starting to trust observation and adaptation over programmed responses.
  </character-development>
